Comments_List:
 Strengths: Wonderful amount of detail;
Weekly quizzes did a great job of reinforcing material;
TF's were marvelous and very well-informed;
I didn't personally use the learning objectives, but they're a great idea for making sure that students get the right takeaways from lectures;
Course is very well-organized and the instructors are very open to feedback;
Poll questions were fun and good ways to review information;
Guest lecturers, for the most part, were interesting and very well-done. The kidney lectures in particular were FANTASTICLY taught and provided me with a load of information in a way that never felt overwhelming. Professor Aronson's lectures were extremely well-organized and made in a way that greatly facilitated my learning.

Weaknesses: Anatomy is not covered, though there's really no time for this, and it's not super necessary;
Pathophysiology was rarely mentioned, which makes sense given the many other things that must be taught, though I must say that pathophysiology provides a great way to better understand normal physiology;
Cardiology lectures were not enjoyable, and I say this as a student who came into this class wanting to be a cardiologist. Professor Boulpaep is a fantastic lecturer, but he moved far too quickly for me to absorb anything he said. Even when professor Campbell covered the rest of cardiology, things were still imperfect because, although his slower pace helped me understand what he was teaching, he often moved too slowly to cover the last few slides of lectures, and these slides often contained the most difficult material. Professors: Please consider finding a balance between these two, so that cardiology can be more fun and less frustrating to understand.
